{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491590"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:54:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:54:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"992"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/992"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.38,0.01,0.42,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"992"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110288"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/992"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"992"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92559"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1120"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"},{"type":"tags","id":"4298"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"6399"},{"type":"tags","id":"6400"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5498"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37544"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41487"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44626"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110288"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 30-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department of a tertiary referral hospital with a 12 hour history of gradual onset left-sided testicular pain. There is no history of trauma and the patient is otherwise well, with no fever, malaise or urethral discharge. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right side of the scrotum and contents appear normal. The left scrotum is swollen, erythematous, and tender on palpation. A cremasteric reflex is present bilaterally and elevating the scrotum briefly relieves the pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urine culture","Urine Nucleic Acid Amplification Test (NAAT)","Testicular tumour markers","Scrotal ultrasound","Surgical exploration"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is most likely presenting with epididymitis with a key differential of testicular torsion. Testicular torsion is more likely if elevation of the scrotum does not relieve the pain (negative Prehn\u0027s sign), but a positive Prehn\u0027s sign does not exclude testicular torsion. Whilst the presence of the cremasteric reflex will usually exclude torsion, this sign is not absolutely reliable and where possible, prompt imaging should always be done in cases such as this one. This patient has presented very soon after the onset of scrotal pain and torsion must be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical exploration\u003C/strong\u003E is of high priority in cases of suspected torsion, if arranged quickly, \u003Cstrong\u003Escrotal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E can differentiate these two key diagnoses through assessing blood flow to the scrotum and avoid further unnecessary intervention. Epididymitis will typically show increased blood flow relating to acute inflammation, whereas torsion will demonstrate decreased blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this patient was younger or scrotal ultrasound was not readily available, surgical exploration would be required to exclude testicular torsion given the high risks associated with missed diagnosis. Obviously if there is going to be any delay with getting an ultrasound examination done, it would be sensible to perform urine culture and urine NAAT. An ultrasound examination should be easily available in metropolitan Emergency Departments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine culture\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eurine NAAT\u003C/strong\u003E will be helpful in establishing a potential cause for this patient\u0027s epididymo-orchitis, with a sexually transmitted infection such as \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoea\u003C/em\u003E more likely in a patient of this age group compared to older men where bacterial causes secondary to urinary stasis may be more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETesticular tumour markers\u003C/strong\u003E such as alpha-fetoprotein, beta-human chorionic gonadotropin, and lactate dehydrogenase would be appropriate in the investigation of a testicular mass or suspected malignancy, but are not indicated in the acute setting of scrotal pain where infection or torsion are the primary concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Testicular Workup for Ischaemia and Suspected Torsion (TWIST) score can be used in the assessment of children with scrotal pain and at risk of testicular torsion, but of less value in adults where epididymo-orchitis is considered a likely cause of the pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epididymitis is a common cause of acute scrotal pain and erythema","Doppler ultrasound is useful in differentiating key causes of scrotal pain","Surgical exploration should not be delayed in cases of scrotal pain with unclear diagnoses in young patients"],"references":["Wright S, Hoffmann B. Emergency ultrasound of acute scrotal pain. Eur J Emerg Med. 2015 Feb;22(1):2-9. doi: 10.1097/MEJ.0000000000000123. PMID: 24910960. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24910960/","Gordhan CG, Sadeghi-Nejad H. Scrotal pain: evaluation and management. Korean J Urol. 2015 Jan;56(1):3-11. doi: 10.4111/kju.2015.56.1.3. Epub 2015 Jan 12. PMID: 25598931; PMCID: PMC4294852. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25598931/","Shunmugam M, Goldman RD. Testicular torsion in children. Can Fam Physician. 2021; 67:669-71."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92559"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"992"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92559"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-29T14:42:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T14:43:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"992"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110288"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"sel